text: Criticizing males who dislike this movie with emotional insults like "they must have tiny balls", is illogical to me. The argument is that if a man dislikes a movie because a woman plays a role, then he is automatically sexist and insecure. What people fail to realize is that it isn't a sense of insecurity or sexism that makes certain men dislike this - it's the fact that it's simply TOO corny.   And people criticizing men in such a manner only lend them strength, as throwing insults towards a large group of people in such a way is inherently disrespectful and will only make them dislike you more.  Not seeing women as a sort of action star figure isn't sexism, and if it is, it isn't wrong. The moment everyone sees everyone as every role is the moment a culture is destroyed, as there is no longer any true substance to any sort of role or character. It's simply "X person could fit in Y role, therefore you can't criticize it when X is Y, as anything which is X can be anything which is Y, and if you do, you're simply insecure X isn't the person you want."  Why of course this is natural! And it allows a culture to improve itself through criticism, what we see now is a degradation of culture in the continuing absence of controversy, rather, "this is a movie. It lacks substance. You cannot criticize ANY of the actors or actresses because its a movie, so obviously, you shouldn't take it seriously." Well shit. If media can never be criticized, and the herd of sheep that is humanity continues to throw their money at it, it will continue to degrade. Such a shame.  The acceptable form of criticism is becoming a criticism of the presence of traditional cultural values a media has. Nothing is funny anymore, nothing has substance, it's simply slapstick, "progressive' ideas of culture, which isn't culture, it's an embrace of an appeal to mediocrity and instant appeal.

text: Yeah I didn't like this film. Maybe I just didn't understand it I dunno (I feel like the movies that get the best reviews by critics are the ones that I simply can't relate to for whatever reason whereas the movies that get the worst reviews, I actually like those). I had no idea what was going on the entire time. The plot was nonexistent, the pacing was really slow, the dialogue was sketchy, the acting was stilted, there were too many scenes of the main character smoking & drinking (as if that's the only thing that makes you a badass) and there weren't enough fight scenes (I went into this thinking it was gonna be like a Fast & Furious movie with non-stop action. Boy was I wrong! And since a lot of people are comparing this film to John Wick, it makes me not want to watch John Wick because that film is probably just as bad). I really wanted to like this movie because we need another epic female action flick, plus, Charlize Theron is an amazing actress. But let's face it, Angelina Jolie is like the only female who's actually good at making action flicks (plus, she probably has better screenwriters and directors for her films). Every other actress pales comparison. Anyway, I kinda regret paying to see Atomic Blonde but at the same time "Pride and Prejudice and Zombies" was even worse (as was the  "Carrie" remake a few years ago and "Hercules" with The Rock) so it's not like Atomic Blonde was the worst movie I paid to see (plus, I recently paid to see "Wish Upon" which was cheesy but I knew that going in. I purposefully paid to see a cheesy teen horror movie and I'm doing it again with "Polaroid" later this month. With Atomic Blonde, as well as PPZ, Carrie & Hercules, I actually expected it to be good but it just wasn't).

text: The movie is good, but it almost completely fails at depicting three things: 80s, DDR and 80s DDR. Just because the plot is in 80s doesn't mean everything is in neon lights and fancy. That might work for USA and Western developed countries, but not DDR. The movie failed at depicting the utter gray depression of Eastern Germany.  Another thing - soundtrack. Using remade songs was a big mistake. Originals should've been used.  Also Theron's looks... she looks completely out of the time and an easy target to notice. Whoever was in charge of clothing has absolutely no idea of what people used to look like in 80s, especially socialist countries.  If the movie depicted these things properly, it could've been more than a good and interesting action movie. It could've been much more. Too bad.
